Checking variable description and rewriting if wrong.¶

  • The histograms in kaggle do not provide an accurate picture of the information.
  • Adult mortality: number of deaths in a population of 1000 that are between the ages of 15-60.
  • Under five deaths: deaths occuring under age 5 in a population of 1000

  • Alcohol is consumed per capita (15+ years) over a calendar year in a country, in litres of pure alcohol

  • Infant mortality rate (dying between birth and age 1 per 1000 live births)

#Afghanistan 

afghan_ad = lifeexp[lifeexp['Country']=='Afghanistan']
afghan_ad.plot.scatter('Year','Adult Mortality',c='blue')

plt.ylabel('Number of deaths/1000')
plt.title('Adult mortality (dying out of a population of 1000) in Afghanistan')

afghan_pop = lifeexp[lifeexp['Country']=='Afghanistan']
afghan_pop.plot.scatter('Year','Population',c='blue')
plt.ylabel('Population in thousands')
plt.title('The Population of Afghanistan')

afghan_ifdeath = lifeexp[lifeexp['Country']=='Afghanistan']
afghan_ifdeath.plot.scatter('Year','infant deaths',c='blue')
plt.ylabel('Infant deaths/1000')
plt.title('Infant mortality rate (dying between birth and age 1 per 1000 live births) in Afghanistan')

afghan_school = lifeexp[lifeexp['Country']=='Afghanistan']
afghan_school.plot.scatter('Year','Schooling',c='blue')
plt.ylabel('Years in School')
plt.title(' The Number of Years in School in Afghanistan')

Summary and conclusion for Afghanistan¶

For the year 2002 the number of adults dying was not in keeping with other years. The adult mortality for other years was between 250 and 300 adults dying in a population of 1000. My conclusion is that the data for population is not accurate. Because of war, I believe that Afghanistan's population is probably not going from high to low. It is probably on the low end. Infant deaths decreased over the years. The number of years that the people in afghanistan have gone to school has increased over the years. Except for two years, that may not be accurate, the Adult Mortality has been decreasing slowly over the years. Infant mortality rate has slowly decreased over the years. It had a sharp decrease starting in the year 2004 until the year 2014. The number of years in schooling had a steep rise in 2005 to 2006. There has been a slow increase in the number of years of schooling. It was below 6 and is now at 10 years.

Summary and conclusion for Mexico¶

The years 2009 and 2013 are not consistent with other adult mortality data. It is not accurate. Population for the years 2007, 2010, and 2013 are not accurate because the population would not change so dramatically from low to high and then to high to low. The infant deaths have steadily decreased in Mexico. The infant mortality has changed from 50/1000 to 33/1000. The number of years of schooling has increased but only by two years in 15 years. It is increasing slowly. 11 years is the equivalent of completing middle school plus one more year of schooling. 13 years is the equivalent of completing high school thus, more people are finishing high school.

#Changing country names to shorter names
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['Venezuela (Bolivarian Republic of)'],'Venezuela')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['Bolivia (Plurinational State of)'],'Bolivia')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['Myanmar (Burma)'],'Myanmar')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['Syrian Arab Republic'],'Syria')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['The former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia'],'Macedonia')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(['Viet Nam'],'Vietnam')
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(["(Federated States of) Monaco"],"Monaco")
lifeexp['Country'] = lifeexp['Country'].replace(["United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland"],'United Kingdom')
#Replace status to 0 or 1
lifeexp['Status'] = lifeexp['Status'].replace(['Developing'],0)
lifeexp['Status'] = lifeexp['Status'].replace(['Developed'],1)

#Using a module to import countries and continents
#create new variable called continent find mean values 

import awoc
import pandas as pd

world = awoc.AWOC()

#Create the dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame(world.get_countries_list(), columns=['Country'])

continent = []
for r in df.iterrows():
        country = r[1]['Country']
        continent.append(world.get_country_data(country)['Continent Name'])

df['Continent']=continent
print(df)

                        "Cabo Verde":"Cape Verde","Ivory Coast":"Côte d'Ivoire","Laos":"Lao Peoples Democratic Republic",

These variables: percentage expenditure, Hepatitis B, BMI, Polio, Total expenditure, Diphtheria, GDP, thinness 1-19 years, thinness 5-9 years and Schooling have high values. Only 4 variables have moderate correlation. The rest have high correlation amongst each other.

Cook's distance¶

The next section deals with Cook's distance. It identifies any outliers in the each of the varaibles

In [27]:
#Import packages to do Cook's distance
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import OLSInfluence

#Cook's distance for Adult Mortality
X = lifeexp_continent[['Adult Mortality']]
y = lifeexp_continent[['Life expectancy ']]
model = sm.OLS(y, sm.add_constant(X))
model_fit = model.fit()

cook_distance = OLSInfluence(model_fit).cooks_distance
(distance, p_value) = cook_distance

#####
threshold = 5/100

# stem plot - the x-axis represents the index of the observation and the y-axis its Cook's distance
plt.stem(distance, basefmt=" ", use_line_collection=True)

# horizontal line showing the threshold value
plt.hlines(threshold, -2, 2950, 'r')

# the observations with Cook's distances higher than the threshold value are labeled in the plot
influencial_data = distance[distance > threshold]

for index, value in influencial_data.items():
    plt.text(index, value, str(index), fontsize=10)

# ticks
plt.xticks(fontsize=14)
plt.yticks(fontsize=14)

# labels and title
plt.xlabel('index', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('cook\'s distance', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Cook\'s Distance for Adult Mortality', fontsize=20);

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) on linear models
from statsmodels.stats.anova import anova_lm

X = lifeexp_continent[['Status','Adult Mortality','Alcohol','percentage expenditure','Hepatitis B','Measles ',
' BMI ','Polio','Total expenditure','Diphtheria ',' HIV/AIDS',
'GDP','Population','Income composition of resources','Schooling']] 
y = lifeexp_continent[['Life expectancy ']]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33)

## fit a OLS model training data
X = sm.add_constant(X_train)
est = sm.OLS(y_train, X).fit()
est.summary()

## fit a OLS model testing data
X = sm.add_constant(X_test)
est = sm.OLS(y_test, X).fit()
est.summary()

#Stepwise regression
#Forward then backward regression
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X =  lifeexp_continent[['Status','Adult Mortality','Alcohol','percentage expenditure','Hepatitis B','Measles ',' BMI ',
                        'Polio','Total expenditure','Diphtheria ',' HIV/AIDS','GDP','Population','Schooling']]

y = lifeexp_continent[['Life expectancy ']]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33)

def forward_selection(X, y, 
                           initial_list=[], 
                           threshold_in=0.01, 
                           threshold_out = 0.05, 
                           verbose=True):
    included = list(initial_list)
    while True:
        changed=False
        # forward step
        excluded = list(set(X.columns)-set(included))
        new_pval = pd.Series(index=excluded,dtype='float64')
        for new_column in excluded:
            model = sm.OLS(y, sm.add_constant(pd.DataFrame(X[included+[new_column]]))).fit()
            new_pval[new_column] = model.pvalues[new_column]
        best_pval = new_pval.min()
        if best_pval < threshold_in:
            best_feature = new_pval.idxmin()
            included.append(best_feature)
            changed=True
            if verbose:
                print('Add  {:30} with p-value {:.6}'.format(best_feature, best_pval))

       
        if not changed:
            break
    return included


result = forward_selection(X_train, y_train)

print('resulting features:')
print(result)

#Backward regression
def backward_regression(X, y,
                           initial_list=[], 
                           threshold_in=0.01, 
                           threshold_out = 0.05, 
                           verbose=True):
    included=list(X.columns)
    while True:
        changed=False
        model = sm.OLS(y, sm.add_constant(pd.DataFrame(X[included]))).fit()
        # use all coefs except intercept
        pvalues = model.pvalues.iloc[1:]
        worst_pval = pvalues.max() # null if pvalues is empty
        if worst_pval > threshold_out:
            changed=True
            worst_feature = pvalues.idxmax()
            included.remove(worst_feature)
            if verbose:
                print('Drop {} with p-value {}'.format(worst_feature, worst_pval))
        if not changed:
            break
    return included

backward_regression(X_train, y_train)

#transform back to dataset

#ridge regression
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

#create train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33)

#for ridge regression 0 to infinity – find more resources
parameters={'alpha':[1e-15,1e-10,1e-8,1e-3,1e-2,1,5,10,20,30,35,40,45,50,55,100]}

#instantiate ridge
ridge=Ridge()

#tune alpha

ridge_regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(ridge_regressor.best_params_)


#Values obtained only find the best alpha on the training data. There is no coef values on grid search CV
#I need to rerun the fit regression on the new alpha without gridsearchcv to find the coefficients 

from pandas import Series, DataFrame

#Alpha comes from grid search
#instantiate the ridge regression

ridge2.fit(X_train, y_train)
pred2 = ridge2.predict(X_test)

mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, pred2)
print("Tuned Ridge Regressor MSE: {}".format(mse))
print("R squared from ridge method: {}".format(ridge2.score(X_test, y_test)))
